{Welcome to the third and final part of this series on the Open Sicilian. In this course, I will cover 2...Nc6 and sides for Black in the Open Sicilian. Concretely speaking, I will be recommending lines against the Sveshnikov Sicilian, Kalashnikov Sicilian, Accelarated Dragon, Grivas Sicilian, Nimzowitsch Sicilian the O'Kelly Sicilian. The approach in this course is to recommend principled variations against the Sveshnikov & Kalashnikov while keeping practical options against the rest. Against the most critical Sveshnikov, I recommend two setups. One with 7.Bg5 & Nd5, leading to a strategically rich game. The other approach is 7.Nd5!?, which often leads to sharp and uncompromising play.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 {the starting point of this course.} Nc6 (2... a6 {The O'Kelly Sicilian. Black hopes for 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 e5!?. Against this, I recommend the easy-to-play and sound setup with} 3. c4 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 e5 {The most critical setup. However, after} 7. Nf5 $5 {White keeps a risk-free edge in most cases.}) (2... Nf6 {The Nimzowitsch Sicilian. This is a very provocative move. Black tempts us to expand with e5.} 3. e5 {we graciously accept the offer!} Nd5 4. Nc3 {We provoke ...Nxc3. This would help us obtain a huge lead in development after dxc3-Bf4.} e6 $5 {The modern way to treat this system. Black wants to undermine the center with ...d6 next. Here, I recommend} 5. Ne4 $5 {provoking ...f5.} f5 6. Nc3 $5 {[%csl Rd5,Re6,Rf5] Black has more weaknesses in their camp compared to the position after 4.Nc3. White usually keeps a big advantage in this system.}) 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {more or less the crossroad for this course. Black has four major options here.} Nf6 (4... e5 {The Kalashnikov Sicilian. This is sounder than it's reputation, often leading to strategically complicated positions. However, after} 5. Nb5 {[%cal Gc2c4] followed by c4, Black needs to be extremely precise to avoid being worse strategically.} d6 (5... a6 {this old line is more or less outdated. Here, I recommend} 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd2 Qg6 9. f3 Nge7 10. Bd3 {[%cal Gb2b3] avoiding all ...d5 tricks. White will develop with b3-Bb2 or Ba3 next.}) 6. c4 {Entering the 'Maroczy' territory. The critical position arises after} Nf6 7. N5c3 Be7 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Be6 10. Be3 Rc8 11. Na3 $5 {[%csl Ga3,Gc3,Gc4,Ge4] White keeps a huge spatial edge in these lines. Blacks need to be very careful not to end up getting worse.}) (4... g6 {The Accelarated Dragon. Black delays ...d6 purposefully. Against this, I recommend a very fresh system with} 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nb3 {[%cal Re7e6,Rd7d5] avoiding all ...e6-d5 ideas. We force Black to convert to the 'Dragon' structures.} O-O 8. Qd2 d6 9. f3 {[%cal Ge1c1] with 0-0-0 & h4 coming up next. Your opponent is out of the book on move 9 in a sharp and complicated territory. I find these lines to be quite tricky for Black to handle.}) (4... Qb6 {The Grivas Sicilian. Black forces us to retreat with our knight.} 5. Nb3 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gc1e3] While the knight on b3 is slightly less active than it was on d4, Black's queen on b6 is quite vulnerable. White would gain a free tempo after Be3 at some point.} Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. Bd3 $5 {[%cal Gd1e2,Gc1e3,Yf2f4] I recommend this simple system against the main line of the Grivas. White maintains flexibility between the plans of Be3-0-0 or Be3-Qe2 & 0-0-0. White usually keeps a big advantage in these variations.}) 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 {The Sveshnikov Sicilian. This is perhaps the soundest Sicilian for Black strategically. Here, I recommend two interesting setups.} 7. Bg5 $5 {This leads to a safer and strategically complicated game.} (7. Nd5 $5 {The other sharper choice.} Nxd5 8. exd5 Nb8 {Black's most trusted defence here.} (8... Ne7 {usually leads to slightly better positions for White. My intended setup here is} 9. c4 {[%cal Gd1a4]} Ng6 10. Qa4 Bd7 11. Qb4 Qb8 12. h4 h5 13. Be3 a6 14. Nc3 Be7 15. Na4 $5 {where White keeps an easier game due to the extra space in the center.}) 9. Qf3 $5 {this leads to a very sharp game. The critical position arises after} a6 10. Qa3 Be7 11. Bg5 f6 12. Bd2 O-O 13. Bb4 axb5 14. Qxa8 Na6 15. Bd2 Qc7 {and here after} 16. c3 $5 {White won easily in 1-0 (41) Erigaisi,A (2712)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2727) Kolkata 2023. Black needs to be extremely precise to navigate these complications.}) 7... a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c4 b4 12. Nc2 {All of this is more or less forced. Here, Black has a few choices.} O-O {This is the modern way of playing. Black doesn't need to spend time on playing ...a5. However, after the typical} (12... a5 {The old main line. Here, I recommend playing} 13. Qf3 Bg5 14. h4 $5 {where the complications favor White.}) (12... Rb8 {can be met with the thematic} 13. b3 O-O 14. h4 $5 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gf6g5,Gh4g5] restricting the bishop on f6.}) 13. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4g5]} a5 14. Qf3 {we reach a position where Black needs to be extremely precise to equalize comfortably. For example, the natural} Be6 {can be met with} 15. Be2 Bxd5 16. cxd5 Nd4 17. Nxd4 exd4 18. Rb1 a4 19. g3 a3 20. b3 $5 {[%cal Ge2d3,Ge1f1,Gf1g2,Gf3e2,Gf2f4] where I think White keeps a risk-free edge. Black struggles to improve, while White has several ways to improve the position.} *

