{[%evp 0,55,36,19,64,61,60,44,44,36,37,30,41,64,48,0,0,-1,-1,-5,13,0,-5,-31,4,4,4,7,9,18,25,-43,8,13,1,10,-12,-27,-2,-30,-30,-11,-3,-47,-40,-23,-32,-32,-22,-25,-22,-27,-27,-27,-27,-27,-27,-25] Welcome to the first chapter. In this chapter, we will start our coverage of the Sveshnikov Sicilian. My first recommendation against Sveshnikov is the positional system with 9.Nd5 Be7 10.Bxf6. Here, I recommend a fresh system with 13.h4!?.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 {One of the two big main moves in the position. Rather than spoiling Black's pawn structure with 9.Bxf6, we are opting the more positional approach with 9.Nd5. The point of this move is to centralize the knight. Further, we can play c3-Nc2 or c4 next.} Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c4 $5 {The more ambitious approach. We hit Black's Queenside and vacate the c2-square for our knight.} b4 $1 {keeping more space on the Queenside.} (11... bxc4 $6 12. Bxc4 $14 {[%cal Ge1g1] In this case, White keeps an unchallenged grip in the center and on the Queenside.}) 12. Nc2 O-O $5 (12... a5 {This and the other sidelines are covered in the second chapter.}) 13. h4 $5 {This rare move is the reason I recommend this system. White gains space on the kingside and stops Black from exchanging the bad bishop with ...Bg5.} (13. Ncxb4 Nxb4 14. Nxb4 Qb6 $11 {White will have to give the pawn back here. We keep a balanced position.}) 13... a5 {the most natural move. Black defends b4.} (13... Be6 {While this is popular, after} 14. Qf3 {we should mostly transpose back to 13...a5 lines.} Bxd5 $6 (14... Be7 15. Be2 a5 {transposes.}) (14... a5 {transposes as well.}) 15. cxd5 Nd4 16. Nxd4 exd4 17. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gf2f4,Yf3e2,Yb2b3,Ya1c1] White gets a better version of the main line. We keep the typical good bishop vs bad bishop scenario.}) 14. Qf3 $5 {This is quite rare, but feels like a very interesting attempt. We threaten to spoil Black's pawn structure on the kingside. More than that, the point is to play Be2-Rd1 next. White's queen is now better placed than it was on f1.} Be6 $5 {The most natural move. Black brings their bishop to the center.} (14... Be7 $5 {This move is a bit rare, but seems stronger. Black has chances to play ...f5 in certain positions.} 15. Be2 {We develop in the typical fashion.} Kh8 $3 {This deep-positional move is the strongest. Black sidesteps all the potential checks and prepares ...f5.} (15... f5 $6 {seems a bit premature. After} 16. exf5 Bxf5 17. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Gc2,Gd3,Gd5] White keeps a bind on the light-squares in the center.}) (15... Be6 {transposes.}) 16. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d8] covering the important d4-square. This move is a prophylactic attempt against ...f5.} f5 (16... Be6 {This is typical, but after} 17. Rd2 Rb8 18. b3 Qd7 19. Nde3 $5 {[%csl Ga2,Gb3,Gc4,Ge4] White keeps an edge due to the complete control of the center.} a4 {The only way to put pressure on White. Black tries to open up the Queenside.} 20. Nf5 axb3 21. axb3 Ra8 22. O-O Ra2 {While Black gets the rook into the game, after} 23. Rfd1 Rb2 24. Nxe7 Qxe7 25. Qe3 {[%cal Gc2b4] I think we maintain some pressure. Here are a few possible lines.} Na5 $5 (25... Qxh4 $6 26. Nxb4 Rxd2 27. Qxd2 $16) (25... Qb7 26. Ra1 Ra8 27. Rxa8+ Qxa8 28. Bd1 $5 {[%cal Ge3d3]}) 26. Na1 Rxd2 27. Qxd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2b4,Gd2d6]}) 17. Nce3 $1 {A very strong idea. We are willing to sacrifice an exchange to lodge our knight on f5.} (17. exf5 $6 {This is premature. After} Bxf5 18. Bd3 {Black has the strong intermezzo to its rescue.} e4 $1 $15 19. Bxe4 Ne5 20. Qe2 Bxh4 $3 $15 {[%csl Re1]}) 17... Nd4 (17... f4 18. Nf5 Bf6 19. h5 $5 {[%csl Gd5,Gf5,Gh5] With obvious pressure due to the active positioning of the knights.}) (17... fxe4 $6 18. Qxe4 $16) 18. Rxd4 $1 exd4 19. Nxf5 Bf6 20. h5 $5 {[%cal Ge2d3] Black cannot do something easily here. I think White's play is easier due to the extra mobility in the position.} Be5 21. Bd3 {Black's play seems difficult. Here are some sample lines.} Qg5 (21... a4 22. Qg4 $16) 22. Kd1 $5 Bb7 23. Nc7 $44) (14... a4 15. Rd1 Be6 16. Be2 {transposes to the next chapter.}) 15. Be2 Bxd5 {The most natural attempt from Black.} ({Another possible idea seems to be} 15... Be7 16. Rd1 Qb8 {[%cal Ge7d8,Gd8b6] preparing ...Bd8-Bb6.} (16... Kh8 {transposes.}) ({defending e7 with} 16... Ra7 {also makes sense, but after} 17. Rd2 Qb8 18. Nxe7+ Rxe7 19. b3 $5 {White keeps the thematic pressure due to the weaknesses on the d-file. A possible line is} a4 20. Qd3 axb3 21. axb3 Rd8 22. O-O Ra7 23. Rdd1 {where we keep some pressure.}) 17. Nce3 $5 Bd8 (17... Bxd5 {can be met with} 18. Nxd5 Bd8 19. h5 h6 20. O-O $14 {Black is unable to play ...Bb6 here, while} Nd4 {runs into} (20... Bb6 21. Nxb6 {[%csl Rd6]}) 21. Rxd4 $1 exd4 22. Bd3 Re8 23. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4] with a typical edge for White. Black is unable to break open up the Queenside.}) 18. Nf5 Kh8 (18... g6 $2 19. Nxd6 $1 $16) 19. g3 g6 {It seems Black is able to play ...Nd4 next, but after} 20. Nfe7 $5 {White is able to keep some pressure.} Bxe7 21. Nxe7 Nxe7 22. Qf6+ Kg8 23. Qxe7 b3 24. a3 Ra6 25. c5 $40) 16. cxd5 Nd4 17. Nxd4 exd4 18. Rb1 {It seems like the position has been liquidated, but in fact if we go deep, White keeps a risk-free pressure. We keep a good bishop vs bad bishop scenario. Our plan is to play g3-f4 at some point. We want to keep expanding on the Kingside.} a4 $5 (18... Qc7 {can be met with} 19. Bd3 a4 20. g3 a3 21. O-O (21. b3 {transposes and seems good too.}) 21... axb2 22. Rxb2 Rfb8 23. Rfb1 $14 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gf3f5,Ge4e5] White keeps a risk-free edge.}) 19. g3 a3 20. b3 $5 {[%cal Ge2d3,Ge1f1,Gf1g2,Ye1e2] Our claim is that Black is unable to progress in a meaningful way.} Qe7 (20... Qc7 21. Bd3 Qc3+ 22. Ke2 Rac8 23. h5 h6 24. Qf5 $16 {While we are improving without any risks, Black cannot do anything worthwhile here.}) 21. Kf1 Rfe8 (21... Rac8 22. Bc4 Rfe8 23. Re1 $14 {[%cal Yf1g2,Yf3d3,Gf2f4]} h5 24. Qd3 Rc5 25. f4 $14 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4,Gf4,Gg3,Gh4]}) 22. Bd3 Rac8 23. h5 h6 24. Kg2 Rc3 25. Rbd1 Be5 26. Qe2 Qg5 27. Kh3 $14 Qe7 28. f4 $14 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4,Gf4,Gg3] White gets the desired break in. Watch out for ...Qd7 ideas. Keep in mind that you will have e5-d6/Bb5 ideas after ...Qd7.} *

