{[%evp 0,32,21,11,60,53,53,30,30,30,41,32,42,49,44,-5,-5,-2,13,11,19,-9,-7,-13,4,4,14,21,19,5,11,10,13,20,4] In the second chapter, we will cover all the sidelines in the Sveshnikov Sicilian system with 7.Bg5.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 {more or less forced.} 8. Na3 {Black has a few choices here.} b5 (8... Be6 $6 {a rare move. However, this has been tried by Shakh a lot. Black stops Nd5. However, after} 9. Bxf6 {Black is under some pressure.} Qxf6 (9... gxf6 $6 {Black spoils their pawn structure for free. A possible idea is} 10. Nc4 Rc8 11. Bd3 Ne7 12. Ne3 h5 13. Qf3 $16 {[%csl Gc3,Rd5,Rd6,Ge3,Rf5,Rf6] White is significantly better due to the weak d5/f5 squares.}) 10. Nd5 Qd8 11. Nc4 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5] White keeps a great due to the central control. We don't need to spend time on routing the a3-knight anymore. A possible line is} g6 12. Ncb6 Rb8 13. Qd2 h5 14. Qc3 $1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gf1a6]} Bxd5 15. Nxd5 $14 {with a clear edge for White.}) (8... Be7 $6 {This allows to play the thematic} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Nc4 $1 {with a stable edge for White.} Nd4 $6 (10... O-O {loses a pawn to} 11. Qxd6 Be6 12. O-O-O $16) (10... Be6 $5 {some players have tried this, but Black doesn't have sufficient compensation. After} 11. Qxd6 Be7 12. Qxd8+ Rxd8 13. a3 O-O (13... Bc5 14. Ne3 Bxe3 15. fxe3 $14 {[%cal Gf1d3]}) 14. Ne3 Bc5 15. Ncd5 $14 {White remains on top.}) 11. Nd5 b5 12. Ncb6 Rb8 13. Nxc8 Rxc8 14. c3 Ne6 15. a4 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Rb5][%cal Gf1a6] With a clear stable advantage for White.}) 9. Nd5 Be7 (9... Qa5+ $6 10. Bd2 Qd8 11. Bd3 Nxd5 (11... Be6 12. c4 bxc4 13. Nxc4 Nxd5 14. exd5 Bxd5 15. Qa4 $18 {[%csl Rc6,Rd5][%cal Gc4e3]}) (11... Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. c4 bxc4 14. Nxc4 $16) 12. exd5 Ne7 13. c4 $16) 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c4 {Black has a few choices here.} b4 $5 (11... Nd4 $5 {This leads to a forced variation with} 12. cxb5 Bb7 (12... O-O 13. b6 $5 Bb7 14. Bc4 Rc8 15. O-O Bxd5 16. Bxd5 Qxb6 17. Nc4 $16 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5,Rd6] The d5-bishop is unchallenged.}) 13. Bc4 $5 axb5 14. Bxb5+ Kf8 15. Bc4 Qa5+ 16. Qd2 Bd8 17. Qxa5 Bxa5+ 18. Kd1 Rc8 19. f3 $14 {White keeps a stable edge. The material advantage has been consolidated.}) (11... O-O 12. cxb5 Nd4 {transposes.}) (11... Bg5 12. cxb5 $16 {outrightly loses a pawn.}) (11... Qa5+ 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Bg5+ 14. Kd1 $16 {White keeps an edge due to the threat of Nc7+.}) 12. Nc2 Rb8 $5 {[%cal Gb4b3]} (12... a5 {Black defends b4-prematurely.} 13. Qf3 $5 {sticking to our usual plan.} Bg5 $6 (13... Be6 {a less played, but a possible option. However, after} 14. Be2 {Black's best bet is to transpose back with} O-O (14... Bxd5 $6 15. cxd5 $16) (14... Be7 15. h4 $5 {transposes.}) 15. h4 $5) (13... Be7 14. h4 Be6 (14... O-O {transposes to the previous chapter.}) 15. Be2 O-O {transposes to the previous chapter.}) 14. h4 $1 {winning a free tempo.} Bh6 (14... Be7 {This gives White a free tempo essentially. Here, we may switch plans and play} 15. g3 O-O 16. Bh3 Be6 17. Rd1 Qb8 18. Kf1 {[%cal Gd1d3,Gf1g2,Gh3f5] with a stable positional edge for White.}) (14... Bxh4 $4 15. c5 $5 dxc5 16. Rxh4 Qxh4 17. Nc7+ Ke7 18. Nxa8 $18) 15. g4 Bf4 16. Nxf4 exf4 17. Qxf4 $16 {[%cal Gf1e2,Gh4h5,Ge1g1,Ye1c1] Black doesn't have sufficient compensation for the missing pawn. We want to safeguard our king next.}) (12... O-O {was covered in the previous chapter.}) 13. b3 {stopping ...b3 ideas.} O-O (13... Bg5 {is weaker and allows us to win a tempo with} 14. g3 O-O 15. h4 $1 Bh6 16. Bh3 Be6 17. Kf1 {[%csl Gc2,Gd5] We keep the typical positional edge here.}) 14. h4 $1 {business as usual.} a5 $5 {Black's most natural response.} (14... Be6 15. g3 $1 a5 (15... Be7 16. Qd3 a5 17. Bg2 $14) 16. Qf3 Be7 17. Rd1 Qd7 18. Be2 {transposes to the main line.}) (14... Be7 15. g3 Be6 {transposes.}) 15. Qf3 Be7 16. Rd1 Be6 17. g3 $5 {defending the h-pawn.} Qd7 18. Be2 Bd8 19. O-O a4 20. c5 $5 $14 {[%csl Gd5,Rd6][%cal Gd1d8] you can stop memorisation here. White exerts a lot of pressure. A possible line is} axb3 21. axb3 Kh8 22. cxd6 Qxd6 23. Bc4 Qc5 24. Rd2 Bb6 25. Rfd1 $14 *

