{[%evp 0,10,33,32,38,41,48,11,27,33,51,51,55] In the third chapter, we will cover the alternate system for White with 7.Nd5. In this chapter, we will cover the positionally sound '8...Nb8'.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 $5 {[%cal Gb5c7] This became popular after the Carlsen-Caruana match. White gives us the hope of controlling the d5-square with a piece in hopes of gaining more space in the center.} Nxd5 8. exd5 Nb8 $5 {Black's most solid response.} (8... Ne7 {This is covered in the next chapter.}) 9. Qf3 {[%cal Gf3c3,Yf3a3] A dual-purpose move. We threaten Qc3. At the same time, we want to stop ...a6 via Qa3.} a6 {The critical response.} (9... Be7 {This is a bit weaker. After} 10. Qc3 Na6 11. Be3 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Gb5a7] White has a good chance of winning the a7-pawn.} O-O (11... b6 $4 12. Qc6+ $18) (11... Bd7 12. Nxa7 $14) 12. Nxa7 $5 {Accepting the pawn without fearing any ghosts.} Bg5 (12... Bd7 13. Bxa6 bxa6 14. O-O-O $14) 13. Nb5 Bxe3 14. Qxe3 f5 15. Qa3 Rf6 16. O-O-O $14 {White keeps a clear due to the extra pawn.}) 10. Qa3 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Ga3a8]} Be7 {The most played move.} (10... b6 $6 {This is played by some players but is weaker. After} 11. Bg5 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gg5d8] Black is under some pressure.} (11. c4 $6 Bb7 12. Nc3 Be7 $11 {Black is able to develop comfortably here.}) 11... f6 12. Bd2 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd2b4,Gb4d6,Gb5d6] keeping an eye on the weak d6-pawn.} Bb7 $5 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ga8a3]} (12... Be7 {This was played in a single game. However, after} 13. Bb4 O-O 14. Bxd6 axb5 15. Bxe7 Qxd5 16. Qd3 $14 {Black is struggling.}) 13. Nc3 Be7 14. O-O-O O-O 15. g4 $1 Nd7 16. Kb1 $14 {[%cal Gd2e3,Gf2f4,Gh2h4] White keeps an easier game due to the potential to gain space on the kingside.}) 11. Bg5 {hoping to deflect the e7-bishop.} f6 {most played.} (11... Bf5 $5 12. Bxe7 Kxe7 13. Be2 $5 {[%csl Re7] While this remains objectively equal, I find it hard to believe that anyone will choose this in a practical game.}) (11... Bxg5 $4 {runs into} 12. Nxd6+ $18) 12. Bd2 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd2b4,Gb4d6]} O-O (12... b6 13. Bb4 $16 {transposes.}) 13. Bb4 {Black has a couple of choices here.} axb5 $5 {The more principled choice. Black sacrifices an exchange to trap our queen on the corner of the board.} (13... Qd7 {This is the other important move.} 14. O-O-O b6 (14... Rd8 15. f4 b6 {transposes.}) 15. f4 $5 {a rare, but a principled try. We increase the pressure in the center.} Rd8 $1 ({the natural} 15... Bb7 $6 {runs into} 16. Nxd6 $1 {and after} a5 17. Bb5 axb4 18. Bxd7 bxa3 19. Be6+ Kh8 20. Nxb7 $16 {[%cal Gd5d6] White remains on top. d6 is coming up next.}) 16. fxe5 fxe5 17. Bd2 Qb7 $1 {The only way to equalise.} ({the natural} 17... Bb7 {runs into} 18. Nc3 b5 19. h4 $16 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5] White will follow up with g4-g5 next. Black has issues with development of the Queenside minor pieces.}) 18. Nc3 b5 19. Qb4 {stopping ...b4.} Nd7 20. Be3 Nf6 (20... Nc5 {runs into} 21. Bxc5 dxc5 22. Qe4 $14 {[%csl Gd3,Ge4,Rh7][%cal Gf1d3,Gd3h7] White keeps good attacking prospects due to the potential pressure on the kingside.}) 21. Bd3 $13 {with a sharp position on the board. Objectively, it remains balanced.}) 14. Qxa8 Na6 15. Bd2 Qc7 $5 {The best move for Black.} (15... Qb6 $6 {This has been played much more frequently but after} 16. Be3 {Black is significantly worse.} Qa5+ $5 (16... Qc7 17. c3 f5 18. Qa7 $18 {our Queen gets away.}) (16... Nc5 $18 17. b4 $18) 17. c3 f5 (17... b4 $2 18. Bxa6 bxc3 19. O-O $18 {White's queen escapes.}) 18. Qa7 Bd8 {[%cal Gd8b6]} 19. f3 $5 {trying to maintain the bishop on the g1-a7 diagonal.} Qa4 20. Bf2 $16 {[%cal Ga7e3]} b6 $5 (20... f4 $4 21. Bd3 $18) 21. Rd1 Qxa2 22. Bd3 Qxb2 23. O-O $16 {White's queen escapes.}) 16. c3 $5 {[%cal Ga8a7] This rare move by Arjun caught my attention. White prepares Qa7.} Qc5 $1 {The cleanest way to equalize. Black stops Qa7.} ({the natural} 16... Bf5 $2 {runs into} 17. Qa7 Nc5 18. Be3 Nd3+ 19. Bxd3 Bxd3 20. Rd1 e4 21. Rxd3 exd3 22. Qb6 $16 {with a clear advantage for White.}) (16... Be6 $4 17. Qa7 Bxd5 18. Bxb5 $18) (16... f5 $5 {this is natural but after} 17. Qa7 {Black has to be very precise to hold.} f4 $5 ({the natural} 17... Nc5 $5 18. Be3 Bd7 $1 {is possible too. A sample line is} 19. Qa3 {[%cal Ge3c5]} b6 20. Be2 f4 21. Bxc5 bxc5 22. Qb3 c4 23. Qc2 Bf5 24. Qd2 Bg5 25. O-O {where White keeps some chances.}) 18. b4 {[%cal Gf1b5,Yb4c5]} Qd7 (18... Bf5 19. Bxb5 $18) (18... f3 $2 19. gxf3 Rxf3 20. Be2 Rf8 21. Qe3 $18 {[%cal Ge1g1] White remains significantly better.}) 19. O-O-O Nc7 20. Be1 $14 {we keep an edge due to the extra material.}) 17. Be3 Qxd5 18. Qa7 f5 19. f3 $5 {While this position is objectively balanced, the position still remains quite sharp from a practical point of view. Here are some sample lines.} f4 $5 ({the natural} 19... Nc5 {can be met with} 20. Bxb5 Bh4+ 21. Kf1 f4 22. Bxc5 dxc5 23. Qa4 {and here Black has only way to equalize.} Qd2 $5 24. Qc4+ Kh8 25. Qe2 $5 Rd8 $1 26. Ba4 {White still keeps some chances here. Black needs to be extremely precise to equalise.}) 20. Bf2 Bf5 (20... Bf6 21. Rd1 Qxa2 22. Bxb5 $16) (20... e4 $2 21. Qd4 $16) 21. Be2 e4 22. Qd4 Qe6 23. fxe4 Bxe4 24. O-O-O {It seems like White is significantly better, but after} Nc5 $1 {Black is able to hold with concrete play.} (24... Bf6 $2 25. Bg4 $1 $18) 25. Bxb5 f3 $1 {the only way to hold.} 26. Rhe1 Bg5+ 27. Be3 f2 28. Bc4 fxe1=R 29. Rxe1 d5 30. Bxg5 dxc4 31. Qxc5 $11 *

