{[%evp 0,43,32,32,41,51,51,33,21,16,51,51,40,35,35,35,35,29,29,29,50,34,21,30,35,34,52,13,37,36,40,39,76,57,57,48,59,36,60,41,37,36,35,32,75,0] In the fourth chapter, we will cover the 8...Ne7 line in the Sveshnikov.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 Nxd5 8. exd5 Ne7 {the starting point of this chapter.} 9. c4 $5 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5][%cal Yd1a4] We gain space in the center and prepare a potential Qa4.} Ng6 {The most played move. Black prepares ...Be7-f5.} (9... Nf5 {This move avoids Qa4, but stops ...f5.} 10. Bd3 $5 {we develop normally and claim a strategic edge due to the extra space.} g6 $5 {the modern way of reacting to this variation.} (10... Be7 {this natural move can be met with} 11. O-O O-O 12. f4 a6 13. Nc3 exf4 14. Bxf4 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Gc4,Gd3,Gd5,Gf4] White keeps an edge due to the extra space and lead in development.}) 11. O-O a6 $5 (11... Bg7 $6 {runs into} 12. Qa4 $1 O-O 13. Qa3 Re8 14. Bxf5 Bxf5 15. Nxd6 Bf8 16. c5 $14 {White keeps an edge due to the extra pawn.}) 12. Bg5 Be7 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Nc3 O-O 15. Qd2 $14 {[%csl Rf5,Rf6,Rg7,Rh6][%cal Gf2f4] with the simple idea of pushing f4 next. Black has weaknesses on the kingside.}) 10. Qa4 $5 Bd7 11. Qb4 {[%cal Gb5d6] Black has two major choices now.} Qb8 {The main move in this position.} (11... Bf5 $5 {This was the choice of Magnus in their Wch match.} 12. h4 $5 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh4h5]} h5 {The most played move.} (12... Be7 13. h5 Nf4 14. Be3 O-O 15. O-O-O $16 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5][%cal Gg2g3] with an unquestionable edge.}) (12... a6 13. h5 Nf4 $5 (13... axb5 {runs into} 14. hxg6 Bxg6 $4 (14... fxg6 15. Qxb5+ $16) 15. c5 dxc5 16. Qxb5+ Qd7 17. Qb6 $18 {[%cal Gf1b5]}) 14. Nc3 Be7 15. Be3 {[%cal Ge1c1] 0-0-0 is coming up next.} Nd3+ {The only way to keep some chances.} 16. Bxd3 Bxd3 17. O-O-O e4 18. h6 $5 {poking holes on the other flank.} g6 19. Rxd3 $1 exd3 20. Qxb7 O-O 21. Rd1 $16 {[%cal Gd1d3] we'll win the second pawn next. White keeps pressure due to the weak Black king and poor pawn structure.}) (12... Nxh4 $4 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Nc7+ $18) 13. Bg5 Qb8 $5 (13... f6 14. Be3 {[%csl Gh4] the h4-pawn cannot be attacked anymore.} a6 15. Nc3 Qd7 16. Na4 $16 {[%cal Ga4b6]}) (13... Qd7 14. Qa5 b6 15. Qa4 $16 {[%csl Rd7,Re8][%cal Gb5c7]}) 14. Be2 a6 15. Nc3 Qc7 $5 (15... Nf4 16. Bxf4 exf4 17. Rd1 g6 18. Bd3 $14) (15... Be7 16. g3 $14 {[%cal Gh4g5,Yg5e3,Gc3a4] we want to play Be3-Na4 next.}) 16. g3 {preparing Be3.} Be7 17. Be3 e4 18. Qa4+ Bd7 (18... Kf8 {runs into} 19. Rd1 Ne5 20. c5 $5 $16) 19. Qb3 f5 20. O-O-O Ne5 21. Kb1 O-O 22. Rd2 $14 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gh1c1,Gc4c5,Gc3a4] White keeps an easier game due to the weak h5-pawn. Our plan is to play Na4-c5-Rc1 next.}) 12. h4 $5 {simple and strong.} h5 $5 (12... a6 $6 {is weaker. After} 13. h5 axb5 14. hxg6 Ra4 15. Qb3 fxg6 16. cxb5 Qa8 17. Bd3 $16 {[%csl Re8,Rg6,Rh7][%cal Gd3g6,Gh1h7] Black is struggling.}) 13. Be3 a6 14. Nc3 Be7 {Here, I recommend playing the correspondence speciality} 15. Na4 $5 {delaying g3 for the moment.} Qc7 {preparing against Nb6.} (15... Nxh4 16. Nb6 $16 {[%csl Ra8]}) 16. g3 $5 {Black has two choices here.} Bg4 (16... O-O 17. Nb6 Rae8 18. Be2 Bf5 {[%cal Ge5e4,Gg6e5] preparing ...e4-Ne5.} 19. f3 $5 {avoiding ...e4. White keeps an easier game due to the extra space.}) 17. Bg2 O-O 18. f3 Bd7 19. Nb6 Rab8 20. O-O-O $14 {[%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5,Gf3f4] our king is safe and we keep extra space. White wants to play a4-a5 & f4 at some point.} *

