{In the fifth chapter, we will begin our coverage of the Kalashnikov Sicilian. Against this, I recommend the 'Maroczy' setup.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 $5 5. Nb5 d6 {Black avoids ...Nf6 and keeps flexibility of pushing ...f5 later. However, this allows White to gain space with} 6. c4 $5 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4]} Be7 {The main move.} (6... Be6 {the second chapter covers sidelines like this.}) 7. N5c3 Nf6 8. Be2 {[%csl Gc1,Gc3,Gc4,Ge2,Ge4][%cal Gc1e3] while White claims that we have a huge spatial advantage, Black wants to play around the weaknesses on d4 & c5.} O-O (8... Nd4 $6 {is a bit premature. We are happy to trade the bad-light-squared bishop on e2. After} 9. Be3 Nxe2 10. Qxe2 O-O 11. O-O Be6 12. h3 a6 13. Nd2 Rc8 14. Rfd1 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Gc4,Gd2,Ge3,Ge4] White keeps a stable spatial advantage.}) (8... Be6 9. Be3 a6 10. O-O O-O {transposes.}) 9. O-O Be6 10. Be3 a6 {[%cal Rb7b5] preparing a potential undermining exercise with ...b5.} (10... Rc8 11. Na3 a6 {transposes.}) 11. Na3 {stopping ...b5.} Rc8 {Black's main move. They remain flexible with their knight.} (11... Ne8 $6 12. Nd5 Bg5 13. Bb6 Qd7 14. Nb1 $14 {[%csl Gb6,Gc3,Gd5][%cal Gb1c3] White's pieces end up on good squares.}) (11... Nd7 12. Nc2 f5 (12... Rc8 13. Rc1 {transposes.}) 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Bg4 $14 {[%csl Gc2,Gc3,Gd5,Ge4] after the light-squared bishop swap, White will end up with complete control of the light-squares in the center.}) 12. Rc1 $5 {We bring our rook into the game as well.} h6 $5 {The modern main line. Black remains flexible and waits for us to play Qd2.} (12... Nd7 {the old main line.} 13. Nc2 f5 (13... h6 {transposes.}) (13... Na5 $6 {runs into the thematic} 14. b3 b5 15. Nd5 $1 bxc4 16. b4 Nb7 17. Na3 $16 {[%csl Rc4] We will recover the c4-pawn next.}) (13... Nc5 14. b4 $16) 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Bg4 $14 {[%csl Ge3,Gg4] with a total grip on the light squares.}) (12... Ne8 {the plan of pushing ...f5 is ineffective in these positions.} 13. Qd2 h6 14. Rfd1 {simple and strong.} Bg5 (14... f5 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Nd5 $14 {[%csl Re7][%cal Ge2d3,Gd2d6]}) 15. Nc2 Bxe3 16. Qxe3 $14 {[%csl Gc2,Gc3,Ge3] White enjoys a healthy advantage. ...f5 weakens the light squares in the center.}) 13. Nc2 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4][%cal Gb2b3] avoiding ...Nxe4 tricks. White prepares b3.} (13. Qd2 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 f5 15. Nc3 f4 $5 $132 {this gives Black good chances.}) 13... Nb8 $5 {This is a very clever way to equalize. Black forcefully captures c4.} (13... Na5 $6 14. b3 b5 {is weaker. After} 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 {Black has given up the center and the light-squared bishop. A possible sequence is} bxc4 17. b4 Nb7 18. Na3 a5 19. b5 Nd7 20. Rxc4 Nbc5 21. Rc2 $16 {[%csl Ra5,Gb5,Rc6,Gd5,Rd6][%cal Ga3c4] White remains better due to the passed b-pawn and the weaknesses on a5/d6/c6.}) (13... Nd7 {this is rare, but quite thematic. However, after} 14. Qd2 {Black is unable to play ...f5/...Nc5 comfortably.} Nc5 (14... f5 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Nd5 $14 {[%csl Gc2,Gd5][%cal Ge2d3] This position is what White dreams of in this structure.}) 15. f3 f5 16. b4 Nd7 17. exf5 Bxf5 18. b5 $16 {with a clear edge.}) 14. Nb4 $5 {sacrificing a pawn to improve the pieces.} (14. b3 b5 $1 $11) 14... Bxc4 15. Bxc4 Rxc4 16. Qb3 $5 b5 (16... Rc8 $6 {this is weaker. After} 17. Nbd5 b5 18. Qa3 Kh7 19. h3 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Rb8,Gc3,Rc8,Gd5,Rd6,Ge3] Black is struggling to improve pieces.}) 17. Ncd5 {taking control of the c-file.} Rxc1 18. Rxc1 Nxd5 (18... Nxe4 $4 19. Rc8 $18) 19. Nxd5 Bg5 20. Qa3 $5 {preventing ...Nd7.} Bxe3 21. Nxe3 Qh4 $5 {The only way to equalize.} (21... Qb6 $4 {runs into} 22. Nd5 Qd4 (22... b4 23. Qf3) 23. Qxd6 $18 {[%cal Gd6f8,Gc1c8]}) (21... Qd7 {this is possible but White maintains pressure nevertheless. A possible sequence is} 22. Nd5 $5 Kh7 23. h3 Rc8 24. Rxc8 Qxc8 25. Qxd6 Nc6 26. Nc7 Qb7 27. Ne8 f6 28. Qd5 $5 {with some chances. White may attack b5/a6 pawns with the knight.}) 22. Qd3 $5 {keeping the pressure intact.} (22. Qxd6 Qxe4 $11) 22... Qf6 23. Nf5 Rd8 24. g3 Qe6 25. Rc7 $44 {While we remain a pawn down, Black's pieces are still paralyzed to an extent.} *

