{[%evp 0,20,32,36,51,59,51,21,21,17,17,-1,-1,-24,-34,-25,-25,-18,17,-7,14,12,36] In this chapter, we will cover Black's alternatives in the Kalashnikov.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 {The starting point of this chapter.} Be6 $5 {a favourite of GM Maghsoodloo. Black delays ...Be7.} (6... a6 7. N5c3 Nf6 {transposes.} (7... Be6 {transposes as well.})) (6... Nf6 7. N5c3 a6 (7... Be7 {transposes to the previous chapter.}) (7... g6 $5 {doesn't change much. After} 8. Be2 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. Be3 Be6 11. Nd2 {we should more or less transpose, say after} a6 ({something like} 11... Nd4 {can be met with} 12. h3 a6 13. Re1 Rc8 14. Bf1 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1,Ga2a4,Yd2b3] where we continue to progress in a risk-free fashion.}) 12. Nf3) 8. Be2 g6 $5 (8... Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Be3 Be6 {transposes.}) (8... Nd4 {can be met with the thematic} 9. Be3 Nxe2 10. Qxe2 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Gc4,Ge4][%cal Ge1g1,Ga2a4,Gb2b3,Gb1d2] with complete control of the center for White.}) 9. Nd2 Bg7 10. Nf3 O-O 11. O-O Be6 12. Be3 $5 h6 (12... Ng4 $6 13. Bg5 Nf6 14. Nd5 $14) 13. h3 $14 {[%cal Gc3d5,Ga1c1,Gb2b3] with a risk-free edge for White.}) (6... g6 7. Bd3 $5 a6 (7... Bg7 8. Be2 $16 {[%csl Rd6]}) (7... Be6 8. N5c3 {transposes.}) 8. N5c3 Bg7 9. Nd5 Nf6 10. Nbc3 $14 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gc1e3,Gd5b6,Ye3b6]}) 7. N5c3 {we bring our knight towards the d5-square. This move anticipates both ...a6 and ...Be7.} g6 $5 {trying to sharpen things by fianchettoing the bishop.} (7... a6 8. Bd3 Nf6 $1 {important.} (8... Be7 9. Nd5 $16 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gc1e3,Ge3b6]}) 9. O-O g6 (9... Be7 10. Nd5 $16) 10. Nd5 $5 Bxd5 11. cxd5 Nd4 {here, I recommend playing} 12. a4 $5 {with the idea of meeting with} Bg7 13. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c4,Ga4a5] with the clear plan of a5 & Nc4 next.}) (7... Nf6 {doesn't have an independent value.} 8. Bd3 $5 Be7 (8... g6 {transposes.}) 9. Nd5 {transposes to the previous chapter.}) (7... Be7 {transposes to the previous chapter.}) 8. Bd3 $5 {defending e4. This helps in playing Nd5 later.} Nf6 (8... Bg7 {one of the two main choices.} 9. Nd5 $5 {staying consistent with the plan.} Nf6 10. Nbc3 Bxd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. cxd5 Nd4 13. Be3 O-O 14. Bxd4 exd4 15. O-O $14 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gf2f4] Black ends up with a bad bishop on g7. White wants to continue to expand with f4 next.}) 9. O-O Bg7 (9... Nd7 10. Na3 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ga3b5] heading over to the weakness on d6.} Bg7 (10... a6 {can be met with the natural} 11. Nc2 Bg7 12. Be3 O-O 13. Be2 $14 {[%csl Gc2,Gc3,Gc4,Ge2,Ge3,Ge4] with a stable and sound edge for White.}) 11. Be2 Nd4 12. Be3 $5 a6 (12... O-O 13. Ncb5 $14) 13. Nc2 Nxe2+ 14. Qxe2 Rc8 15. b3 $5 {If Black doesn't challenge our center, we might end up having a huge spatial edge. Therefore, they are forced to play} b5 {but after} 16. Rfd1 bxc4 17. b4 $5 Qc7 18. a4 O-O 19. a5 $14 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4] white keeps a spatial edge.}) 10. Nd5 Bxd5 (10... O-O 11. Nbc3 $14 {with a stable edge for White.}) (10... Nd7 11. Nbc3 O-O 12. Be3 Nd4 13. b3 $14 {White remains better due to the extra space and centralized knight. We might want to play Qd2-Bh6 next.}) 11. cxd5 $5 {with a concrete decision in mind.} Nd4 12. Bg5 h6 13. Be3 O-O 14. Na3 Nd7 15. Rc1 Rc8 16. Rxc8 Qxc8 17. Qd2 Nc5 18. Bb1 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4] White remains better due to the pair of bishops. We want to open up the kingside with f4 next.} *

