{[%evp 0,37,17,13,44,47,51,0,0,19,12,0,35,35,35,23,30,15,28,30,30,36,27,22,23,22,49,-27,-4,5,13,21,9,28,5,14,39,35,41,54] In this chapter, we will cover the 5..a6 line in the Kalashnikov Sicilian.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 a6 {Black delays ...d6. We can try to exploit this with} 6. Nd6+ $5 {and after} Bxd6 7. Qxd6 $5 {[%csl Gc1,Gf1] White claims an advantage due to the pair of bishops.} Qf6 {The most played move. Black wants to exploit their lead in development.} (7... Qe7 {This is the other critical move in the position. Black hopes for Qxe7 Ngxe7.} 8. Qd1 $5 Nf6 9. Nc3 d6 10. Bg5 {[%cal Gc3d5] This is why giving up the dark-squared bishop so early isn't great.} Be6 11. Nd5 {hoping to win the other bishop. After} Bxd5 12. exd5 Nb8 13. c4 Nbd7 14. Be2 h6 15. Be3 O-O 16. O-O $16 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5,Ge2,Ge3] White keeps a stable advantage due to the pair of bishops and extra space in the center.}) 8. Qd2 $5 {a rare, but challenging move. We want to play Nc3 next.} (8. Qxf6 {this is the most played move. However, after} Nxf6 9. Nc3 Nb4 10. Kd2 d6 $132 {Black keeps decent chances.}) 8... Qg6 {Black's main move in the position.} (8... Nge7 9. Nc3 O-O (9... d6 {can be met with the thematic} 10. b3 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gc1a3]} O-O 11. Bb2 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gf2f3] with 0-0-0 & Bd3 coming up next. White's has a better version of 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 d6 3.d4 line.}) 10. b3 {This leads to a better version of the 'Magnus Sicilian' with 2.Nc3 3.d4.} b5 11. Bb2 d6 12. O-O-O $16 {[%csl Rd6]}) 9. f3 $5 {avoiding Nc3. we avoid ...d5 lines due to this.} (9. Nc3 Nge7 10. h4 h5 11. Qg5 Nb4 $132 {leads to positions where Black may survive.}) 9... Nge7 (9... Nf6 {can be met with} 10. b3 O-O 11. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gb1c3]}) (9... d5 $4 10. exd5 Nd4 11. Na3 $18 {[%cal Gc2c3]}) 10. Bd3 $5 {avoiding ...d5 lines.} d6 (10... O-O 11. b3 $14 {[%cal Gc1a3,Gb1c3] with the thematic Ba3 or Nc3 coming up next.}) 11. b3 $5 {[%cal Gc1a3] preparing Ba3 as usual.} f5 12. Nc3 fxe4 13. fxe4 O-O 14. Ba3 {[%csl Rd6] hitting d6. White prepares 0-0-0.} Bg4 {the only way to complicate matters. Black stops 0-0-0.} 15. h3 $5 Qh5 {desperately hanging on to the g4-bishop.} 16. Qe3 {[%cal Gg2g3] avoiding ...Qh4+.} Rad8 17. Rf1 Rxf1+ 18. Kxf1 Be6 19. Kg1 $14 {Our king remains safe. White remains better due to the pair of bishops.} *

