{[%evp 0,31,17,13,43,41,43,28,9,9,79,66,58,2,23,23,8,3,1,-1,5,2,-3,0,-1,-5,19,14,25,24,33,23,51,-105]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 (2... g6 {starting with this doesn't change much. After} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bg7 5. Nc3 Nc6 {we transpose.}) 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 {Here, I recommend the very fresh} 6. Nb3 $5 {with the idea of transposing into a Dragon-sicilian-like position. There are some subtle differences which we will explore in this chapter.} Nf6 (6... d6 {starting with this is possible too.} 7. Be3 Bxc3+ $5 {the only independent try.} (7... Be6 8. Qd2 Nf6 9. f3 {transpose.}) (7... Nf6 {transpose.}) 8. bxc3 Nf6 9. Bd3 $5 {[%csl Rg7,Rh6] While we keep an inferior pawn structure, Black has huge holes around their king.} O-O (9... d5 10. exd5 Qxd5 11. O-O $14) (9... Qc7 10. Qd2 $14) 10. O-O {[%csl Gd3,Ge3,Rg7][%cal Gd1d2,Ge3h6] White remains better due to the extra space and pair of bishops. h6/g7 are weak.}) (6... a5 $6 7. a4 Nf6 8. Bb5 $14 {[%csl Gb5]}) (6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Nf6 8. Bd3 O-O {this allows White the extra possibility of playing} (8... d5 9. exd5 Qxd5 10. O-O $14 {[%cal Gc3c4,Gc1b2,Gb2h8] c4 comes up next.}) 9. c4 $14 {[%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5] stopping d5. We might continue with a4-a5 at some point.}) 7. Be3 {We develop normally.} O-O {the most natural move.} (7... d6 {starting with this makes sense as well.} 8. f3 {going for the typical Yugoslav pawn structure.} Be6 $5 {[%cal Gd6d5] preparing a quick ...d5.} (8... O-O 9. Qd2 {transposes.}) 9. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1]} d5 $5 10. exd5 {This liquidation process is usually good for White in the Sicilian structures, provided that we end up with the control of the d-file.} Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. Qxd5 Bxd5 13. O-O-O {[%cal Gd1d8]} O-O-O $1 (13... Be6 14. Nc5 $1) 14. Bb5 $5 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Gb5c6,Ge3a7] poking holes on the Queenside.} a6 (14... Kc7 15. Nc5 $14) 15. Be2 $5 {[%csl Rb6,Rd5][%cal Ge3b6,Yc2c4,Yb3c5] hoping to occupy the d-file next with Bb6. White keeps some pressure.}) (7... a5 $6 8. Nd5 $16 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ge3b6]}) 8. Qd2 d6 (8... Ng4 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bf4 $14 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gf2f3] White essentially wins a free tempo here.}) 9. f3 {we reach a Dragon Sicilian position but with our knight on b3. This helps in preventing ...d5 in a lot of these lines.} Be6 $5 {[%cal Gd6d5] preparing a quick ...d5.} (9... a5 {this move almost never works. After} 10. a4 $16 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gf1b5] White is much better placed.}) (9... a6 $6 {is a bit too slow. After} 10. O-O-O b5 11. h4 h5 12. Bh6 $14 {White keeps great attacking prospects.}) (9... Bd7 {is a bit slow too. After} 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Kb1 Ne5 12. Be2 $14 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gh2h4] White will continue to improve with the typical g4/h4 coming up next.}) 10. O-O-O {We stop that!} Rc8 {The most natural imo. However, White has nothing to fear here.} (10... a5 11. a4 $16 {[%cal Gc1b1,Gf1b5] White keeps the usual bind here.}) (10... Ne5 11. Kb1 a6 $5 {[%cal Gb7b5]} (11... Nc4 $2 {can be met with} 12. Bxc4 Bxc4 13. Bh6 $16 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gh2h4]}) (11... Rc8 {transposes.}) 12. h4 h5 13. Be2 Rc8 (13... Nc4 $6 14. Bxc4 Bxc4 15. g4 $16) (13... b5 14. Bh6 $14 {[%cal Gb3d4,Gg2g4]}) 14. Bd4 $5 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gg2g4,Gd4c3]} Qc7 15. g4 $5 {sacrificing a pawn to open up the kingside.} hxg4 (15... b5 16. gxh5 $14) 16. f4 Nc6 17. Bxf6 $16) (10... a6 {is a bit too slow as usual.} 11. Kb1 b5 12. h4 h5 13. g4 $16) (10... Qc7 $1 {[%cal Gd6d5] This is the only concrete solution that equalizes. Black vacates the d8-square for their rook and prepares a potential ...d5. However, I don't find this to be natural for Black.} 11. h4 $5 h5 {one of the most natural reactions.} (11... Rfc8 $5 {this is again not a simple idea. playing ...Qc7+Rfc8 doesn't seem natural.} 12. Kb1 Ne5 13. Bh6 Bxh6 14. Qxh6 {It seems like White is putting a bit of pressure here but after} Qb6 $1 {[%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4] we are forced to retreat with} 15. Qd2 h5 {with a balance position on the board say after} 16. Be2 $11) (11... d5 12. Bf4 $5 {a small practical try.} (12. exd5 Rfd8 13. Bf4 Qb6 14. Be3 Qc7 $11) 12... Qb6 $1 {this equalizes by force.} (12... Qc8 $6 13. exd5 Rd8 14. d6 $14 {[%cal Gf4h2,Yf6h5] we are able to put some pressure here.}) 13. Na4 Qd8 14. Nac5 dxe4 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Qe1 Qc8 17. Kb1 $5 $11 {the game goes on but from an objective point of view, Black has completely equalised.}) 12. Kb1 Rfd8 {this doesn't work now. After} (12... Rfc8 $5 13. Nb5 Qd7 14. Bh6 a6 (14... Bh8 15. g4) 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Nc3 b5 17. Be2 {[%cal Gb3d4,Gg2g4] with some pressure for White.}) 13. g4 d5 (13... hxg4 14. Nd5 $14 {[%cal Gh4h5]}) 14. Bf4 Qc8 15. e5 {White is seriously pushing here.}) 11. Kb1 Ne5 12. Be2 Nc4 {natural. However, after} (12... Bc4 13. f4 $14 {[%cal Ge4e5]}) (12... a6 13. h4 h5 {transposes.}) 13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14. h4 $14 {Black is struggling. for example,} h5 $6 {runs into} 15. e5 Ne8 16. g4 $1 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gg4h5]} Bxe5 17. gxh5 $18 *

