{[%evp 0,15,32,36,51,51,51,21,21,17,44,77,72,62,82,54,57,49] We now begin our exposure of the sidelines in the Sicilian system. The ninth chapter will cover the 'Grivas Sicilian'.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qb6 $5 {putting pressure on the knight on b6.} (4... a6 5. Nc3 e5 $6 (5... e6 {transposes to the 'Taimanov' Sicilian. We cover this in part two of the Sicilian series.}) 6. Nf5 d6 7. Ne3 $16 {[%csl Gc3,Ge3][%cal Ge3d5] we get a better version of the Sveshnikov Sicilian as the knights are much better placed.}) 5. Nb3 {Black has a couple of choices here.} Nf6 $5 (5... e6 {delaying ...Nf6 also makes sense.} 6. Nc3 a6 (6... Nf6 {transposes.}) 7. Bf4 $5 {preventing ...Qc7.} Nf6 $5 (7... Bb4 $2 {runs into} 8. Qg4 {[%csl Rg7]} g6 (8... Kf8 9. Qe2 $16 {is also quite sad for Black.}) 9. Qf3 $18) 8. a3 $5 {[%cal Ga3b4] stopping ...Bb4. We want to play e5 next.} Ne7 {the choice of the GM's that opted for this system. Nevertheless, after} (8... Be7 9. e5 $18) (8... e5 9. Bg5 $16 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc3d5,Gg5f6]}) (8... d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Qxd5 Be6 12. Qe4 $16 {Black doesn't have sufficient compensation for the missing pawn.}) 9. Qe2 Ng6 10. Bd2 Qc7 11. g3 b5 12. Bg2 Rb8 13. f4 Bb7 14. e5 $16 {[%csl Ge5,Gf4,Gg3] White keeps a huge spatial edge.}) 6. Nc3 e6 {[%cal Gf8b4]} (6... d6 7. Be3 Qc7 8. f4 $16 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4] we have a free tempo in the Rauzer. White stands significantly better.}) 7. Bd3 $5 {simple and strong. We defend the e4-pawn anticipating ...Bb4.} a6 (7... d6 8. Be3 Qc7 9. f4 a6 (9... Be7 {tr.}) 10. Qe2 b5 {tr.}) (7... Be7 8. Be3 Qc7 9. f4 d6 10. g4 a6 11. g5 Nd7 12. Qd2 $16) (7... Bb4 {runs into} 8. O-O O-O 9. Be3 Qc7 10. f4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4] If Black doesn't take on c3, we will keep a simple space advantage. White essentially has an extra tempo in the 'Scheveningen' system.} Bxc3 11. bxc3 {[%cal Ge4e5]} d6 (11... d5 $6 12. e5 Ne4 13. c4 $16 {[%csl Gd3,Ge3]}) (11... e5 12. f5 $16 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5,Gc3c4]}) 12. Qf3 {including all the pieces into the action on the kingside.} b6 (12... Bd7 13. Rae1 $16 {[%cal Gc3c4] White keeps great attacking prospects.}) 13. Rae1 Bb7 14. Qh3 d5 15. e5 Ne4 16. c4 $16 {[%csl Gd3,Ge3] we'll eliminate the weakness with cxd5 next. White remains better due to the advantage of a pair of bishops and extra space on the kingside.}) 8. Qe2 {[%cal Gc1e3,Ge1c1,Ye4e5] preparing Be3 & 0-0-0.} d6 (8... Qc7 9. f4 d6 10. Be3 {transposes.}) 9. Be3 Qc7 10. f4 b5 $5 (10... Be7 11. O-O-O b5 12. g4 $14 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4,Gg4][%cal Gg4g5] this is the pawn structure white usually wants. We have an incredible space advantage.}) 11. O-O-O Be7 (11... Bb7 12. g4 $16) 12. g4 Bb7 13. g5 Nd7 14. Kb1 O-O 15. Rhf1 $16 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gf4f5] White remains better due to the extra space on the kingside.} *

