{In this chapter, I will be recommending 3.c4 against the 'O'kelly sicilian'.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6 {Black is hoping for 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 e5!?.} 3. c4 $5 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4][%cal Gc4b5] preventing ...b5. White claims to get the desired 'Maroczy bind' in.} Nc6 {Black's most trusted choice.} (3... e6 4. Nc3 {This leads to desirable structures in the 'Kan/Paulsen' Sicilian for White.} Nc6 $5 (4... Qc7 {can be met with the thematic} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. a3 {[%cal Ga3b4] preventing ...Bb4. After} Nf6 {White may opt for the natural and strong setup with} 8. Be3 {with moves like Be2-Rc1-0-0-f3 coming up next.} Be7 9. Rc1 b6 10. Be2 Bb7 11. f3 $14 {we keep a huge spatial advantage.}) 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Bb4 $6 (6... Nf6 $6 7. Nxc6 dxc6 (7... bxc6 8. e5 $16) 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Ge1c1,Gc3a4] Black's king remains vulnerable.}) (6... Qc7 7. a3 {transposes.}) 7. Nxc6 dxc6 (7... bxc6 8. Qd4 $16) 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Bf4 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gh2h4] we'll follow up with 0-0-0 & h4-f3-h5-g4 next. White keeps a better position due to the extra space and a safer king.}) (3... d6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 $14 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4] White's able to get a maroczy bind in. This is our dream setup against the ...d6 lines. With 2...d6 and 4...Nf6, White has no time to get this setup in.}) 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 {The most played move.} (5... e6 6. Nc3 {transposes.}) (5... Nf6 6. Nc3 {should ideally transpose.} e5 (6... Qc7 7. Be3 $16 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Ga1c1,Gc1c7]}) 7. Nf5 d6 (7... d5 {transposes.}) 8. Ne3 {transposes.}) (5... d6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Be2 e6 8. Be3 $14 {White keeps a thematic edge due to the extra space in the center.}) (5... g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. Nc3 d6 8. Be2 Nf6 9. h3 O-O 10. O-O {we transpose to Accelarated Dragon positions. However, these lines are quite comfortable for White.} Nxd4 $5 {not giving us the time to play Nf3.} (10... Bd7 {can be met with} 11. Nf3 {[%csl Gc3,Ge2,Ge3,Gf3] keeping more pieces on the board.} Rc8 12. Rc1 {[%cal Gb2b3]} Qa5 (12... Na5 13. b3 $16 {[%csl Ga2,Gb3,Gc4,Ge4]}) 13. Qd3 $5 {[%cal Gd3b5] stopping ...b5.} Rfd8 (13... Nb4 14. Qb1 $16 {[%cal Ga2a3]}) 14. Rfd1 Be8 (14... Be6 15. Nd5 $18) 15. a3 $16 {White keeps a risk-free spatial edge.}) 11. Bxd4 Bd7 (11... Be6 12. b3 Nd7 13. f4 $16 {[%csl Ga2,Gb3,Gc4,Ge4,Gf4] We build a massive spatial edge in the center.}) 12. Re1 Bc6 13. Qc2 Nd7 (13... Rc8 14. Qd3 Nd7 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. b4 $16 {stopping ...Nc5. White remains better.}) 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. b4 $14 {[%cal Ge2g4,Ga2a4] White keeps an edge due to the extra space.}) 6. Nf5 $5 d5 {This is the critical try here. Black challenges our center.} (6... d6 7. Ne3 Nf6 8. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Ge3d5] White keeps a risk-free edge due to the extra space in the center.}) 7. cxd5 Bxf5 8. exf5 Nd4 9. Nc3 {[%csl Gd5] White banks on the fact that they have a passed pawn and the pair of bishops.} Nf6 (9... Be7 10. g3 Nf6 11. Bg2 $14 {[%csl Gd5] with a sound strategic edge for White.}) (9... Ne7 $5 10. Bd3 Nxd5 (10... Nexf5 11. O-O $16 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 11. O-O Bb4 $5 (11... Be7 12. Be4 $16 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gb2c3,Ge4b7]}) (11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 $18) 12. Be4 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Bxc3 14. Rb1 O-O 15. Qg4 $16 {[%cal Gc1h6,Gb1b7] with a potential assault on the Kingside.}) (9... Nxf5 $4 10. Qa4+ $18) 10. Bd3 Be7 $5 (10... Nxd5 {transposes.}) 11. O-O O-O (11... Nxd5 {transposes.}) 12. Re1 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Qg4 {[%cal Gc1h6]} Bf6 15. Bh6 Qd7 16. Rad1 Rad8 17. h4 {gaining space on the kingside.} Rfe8 18. b3 $5 Qc8 (18... b5 19. Be4 $5 {[%cal Gh6e3]}) 19. h5 Kh8 20. Be3 h6 21. Rc1 Qd7 22. Be4 $14 {[%csl Ge3,Ge4,Rf6,Gg4] White keeps an edge due to the pair of bishops and the bad bishop on f6.} *

