{In the final chapter, we will cover the 'Nimzowitsch Sicilian.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 $5 {Black challenges the center immediately without stopping e5.} 3. e5 {needless to say, we should expand whenever possible. White gains space.} Nd5 4. Nc3 $5 {we are willing to spoil our pawn structure in hopes of quick development.} e6 $5 {[%cal Gd7d6] The modern way of treating this system. Black wants to undermine our center with ...d6 next.} (4... Nxc3 5. dxc3 Nc6 6. Bf4 {[%csl Rc8,Rd7,Gf3,Gf4] Black has problems with development.} e6 $5 {Black's main move in the position.} (6... Qb6 {doesn't change much.} 7. b3 Qc7 8. Qd2 e6 9. h4 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gh4h5,Gh1h3] we will follow up with the thematic h5-Rh3 & 0-0-0 next. White is better due to the better-developed pieces and extra space.}) (6... d5 $6 7. exd6 exd6 8. Qd2 $16 {[%csl Gf3,Gf4][%cal Ge1c1]}) (6... Qc7 $5 7. Qd2 $16 {[%cal Gh2h4,Ge1c1] we will follow up with 0-0-0-h4 & Rh3 next.}) 7. h4 $5 Qc7 8. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gh4h5,Gh1h3] with the thematic 0-0-0-h5-Rh3 coming up next. White remains better.}) 5. Ne4 $5 {[%cal Gc2c4] threatening to break open the center with c4 & d4.} f5 {the most trusted choice of Black players.} (5... Nc6 6. c4 Nb6 (6... f5 $5 7. Nxc5 Bxc5 8. cxd5 Nd4 $5 (8... exd5 9. d4 $16) 9. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4]} Qc7 10. b4 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 Qxe5+ 12. Be2 Bd4 13. O-O O-O 14. Bc4 $14) 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nd6+ Bxd6 9. exd6 Qf6 10. Bd3 e5 11. c5 Nd5 12. O-O O-O 13. Be4 Nf4 14. Bxf4 Qxf4 15. Re1 $18) 6. Nc3 $5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc3d5] Nxd5 is now much more effective as Black has more weaknesses on the kingside.} Nb4 $5 {the most critical move. Black discourages d4.} (6... Nc7 $6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Bg5 {Black will need to trade the bishops. That would weaken the d6-square considerably.}) (6... Nc6 {can be met with} 7. Nxd5 exd5 8. d4 d6 9. Bg5 Be7 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Bb5 $16 {Black has too many weaknesses in their camp.}) (6... Nxc3 7. dxc3 Be7 8. h4 $16 {[%cal Gc1f4,Gd1d2] with the thematic Bf4 & Qd2-0-0-0 coming up next.}) 7. a3 $5 N4c6 8. b4 {sacrificing a pawn to build a massive center.} cxb4 $5 {principled, but weak.} (8... d5 {this has been tried by most players, but after} 9. exd6 Bxd6 10. Bc4 O-O (10... Nd4 11. Nb5 $1 $14 {Black has significant weaknesses in their camp.}) 11. bxc5 $14) (8... b6 9. b5 Na5 10. g3 $14) 9. Nb5 $1 bxa3 (9... a6 10. axb4 $1 Bxb4 11. c3 Be7 12. d4 $16 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge5]}) 10. Rxa3 $5 a6 (10... Bxa3 11. Bxa3 $18) 11. Nd6+ Bxd6 12. exd6 O-O 13. h4 $18 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gf1e2,Yd2d4] even though we remain a pawn down, White remains significantly better due to the massive difference in activity of the pieces.} *

